I've seen a lot of relationships come and go, both personally and amongst my friends, over the years. A good RL friend of mine is 28 and has been married and divorced 3 times already. Her current beau has now proposed to her after they have been seeing each other exclusively and seriously for about a year. I moved out of town before I had a chance to meet him, but I'm more comfortable with this marriage than her previous one (she had already been divorced 2x when I met her). I was thinking about inviting the two of them to visit this summer, and was contemplating the things I'd say to him if/when I met him; you know, the usual inanities: &quot;It's nice to finally meet you... I've heard so much about you... I'm glad she was finally able to pick one that treats her well...&quot;<br>
<br>
The gist:<br>
Then it occurred to me: she has never said anything bad about this guy to me, and she has had plenty of opportunity to vent. Her previous husband (and the two before him) were complained about pretty frequently. I then applied this filter to my own current relationship (with Mrs. Chase-to-be), and could not recall a single time when I had badmouthed her, either. We have had our disagreements, to be sure, but we worked them out calmly and rationally, and one or the other of us is usually able to successfully win the other to our point of view to achieve harmony.<br>
<br>
The question:<br>
So is that how you know that you, or any of your friends, have finally found &quot;the one?&quot; I realize that a certain amount of griping is to be expected, and it's healthy to be able to discuss the faults you perceive in your significant other with a good friend, but what if neither you nor your friends have anything bad to say? Is that the only way to know for sure? What other positive (or negative) signs do you pick up on to know whether or not a relationship is on solid ground?<br>
<br>
